               <head>Akbarnāmah. Vol. 3, by Abū al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak</head>

               <msContents
                  class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n80002413 
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh85064913 
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2008115921 
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2008115920">

                  <summary><title>Āʾīn-i Akbarī</title>, the third book or supplement of the
                     <title>Akbarnāmah</title> by Abū al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak, containing a detailed statistical description of
                     the Mughal empire in India. </summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_6-item1">
                     <author key="viaf_5150639">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Abū al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak,
                           1551–1602</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">أبو الفضل بن مبارك</persName>
                     </author>

                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20880">Āʾīn-i Akbarī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa">آئين اكبری</title>

                     <incipit xml:lang="fa">(f. 13v) اى همه در پرده نهان راز تو
                        ...</incipit>
                     <colophon>Completed on the 17th of Ẕu'l-Qaʿdah (year omitted) by Muḥammad
                        Ḥusayn Kāshī</colophon>

                     <note>
                        <p>Full index of contents on ff. 1v–12v. </p>
                        <p>Ff. 51v, 52r, 241v, 332r, and 332v are left blank. </p>
                     </note>

                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>

               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <extent>ff. 365 <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>330</height>
                              <width>229</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>Persian foliation 1-354, beginning on f. 13, and European pencilled
                              foliation 1-365 every fifth leaf. </p>
                        </foliation>

                        <condition>
                           <p>Fair. </p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>

                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="21">
                           <p>21 lines per page. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>

                  <handDesc>
                     <summary/>
                     <handNote>
                        <p>Nastaʿlīq script in black ink with headings and overlinings in red.
                           Copyist <persName role="scr">Muḥammad Ḥusayn Kāshī</persName>. </p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>Text frames in red ink. </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>

                  <additions>
                     <p>Ff. 1v-12v: full index of the contents of this work which was added earlier
                        than 1720. </p>
                     <p>Flyleaf and f. 13r: signatures ‘Mr Richard Johnson’. </p>
                     <p>Folio 1r: note recording a transfer from <persName role="asn" key="person_f8882">Akram al-Dīn</persName>
                        to <persName role="asn" key="person_f8882">Mullā Rashīd</persName> dated 10 Jum II 1132 (19 April 1720),
                        and inspections dated 9 Shavval 1134 (23 July 1722), 23 Jumadi II 1139 (15
                        Feb 1727) and 19 Shavval? year 21 (of Muhammad Shah = 30 Jan 1739). </p>
                     <p>Folio 1r: rectangular seal of former owner <persName role="fmo" key="viaf_57907434">Lachhmī Narāyan
                           Shafīq</persName> with his note in Persian recording that he acquired vol
                        3 of the Akbarnāmah through Ḥājjī Sulṭān <hi rend="italic">ṣaḥḥāf</hi> on 25 Jumadi I 1177 (1 Dec
                        1763). Also that it was part of a three volume set costing Rs 157. </p>
                     <p><persName role="fmo" key="viaf_287207857">Richard Johnson</persName>'s acquisition statement in Persian that this was one of 11
                        vols purchased in Hyderabad for Rs 500: <hi rend="italic">Dar Ḥaydarābād
                           mujtamalah yāzdah jild kih ba-qaymat-i pānṣad rūpīyah kharīdah shud ...
                           dākhil-i kutubkhānah</hi></p>. 
                  </additions>

                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1930" notAfter="1960">
                        <p>Half cloth mid-20th century binding over large-curl marbled boards.</p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal subtype="rectangle" type="stamp">
                        <p>Rectangular seal of former owner <persName role="fmo" key="viaf_57907434"
                              >Lachhmī Narāyan Shafīq</persName> (f. 1r): <hi rend="italic">Lachhmī
                              Narāyan 1168 (1754/55)</hi>. </p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
                        <p>Oval stamp (ff. 1r, 365v): ‘EI Company Library’.</p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
                        <p>Oval stamp (flyleaf): ‘India Office Library’.</p>
                     </seal>

                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>

               <history>
                  <origin>17 Ẕū al-Qaʿdah (year not specified), <origDate calendar="Hijri-qamari"
                        notBefore="1750" notAfter="1850">late 17th or early 18th century </origDate>
                     <origPlace>India</origPlace>
                  </origin>

                  <provenance>
                     <p>Inspections dated between 10 Jumadi II, 1132 (19 April 1720) and 19 Shavval?
                        year 21 (of Muhammad Shah = 30 Jan 1739) suggest that it was part of a major
                        library collection. </p>
                     <p>Acquired by <persName role="fmo" key="viaf_57907434">Lachhmī Narāyan</persName> in 1177/1763 for RS 157 from Ḥājjī Sulṭān the
                        bookbinder, part of a 3 vol. set (with IO islamic 1 and 2). </p>
                     <p>Acquired by <persName role="fmo" key="viaf_287207857">Richard Johnson</persName>, East India Company Resident in Hyderabad
                        1784-5, as one of a collection of 11 volumes purchased for Rs 500. </p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>The Johnson collection—comprising 64 albums of paintings and an estimated
                        1,000 manuscripts—was purchased by the East India Company Library for 3,000
                        guineas on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1807-02-18">18 February
                           1807</date>. </p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>

